It depends on the couple. The sort of people they are, how deeply they know each other, how soft each person is. It takes a really sickly-sweet relationship to go straight into full, bare-faced compliments.
Remember, conversations are almost always 'contests' where at least one participant wants something the other has. Anything from learning a secret to understanding what's going through the other person's head for altruistic reasons.
To that end, teases and poking a little fun at one another works wonders. It's probing their 'defenses' and earning some jabs back to get that engagement.
"You're adorable when you pout/you're grumpy," is the sort of tease you need to get the ball rolling. It's playful while also offering a back-handed compliment while showing concern. You could also do worse than have one partner start hugging the other or showin affection in some way to also get the receiver to ask what they did to earn it. I'm sure once you get started, and if you have the characters well defined in your mind, you'll let the dialogue happen organically.
I only find getting into the "I love you"'s and "you're handsome/beautiful" and such as being really deep in the moment, and there's a lot of ground to cover before then. Again, without knowing the characters, it's hard to give more pointed advice.
